<DocSection Title="Before you start">
    <p>This page assumes you've already:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Installed the prerequisites and template — <MudLink Href="/get-started/installation">Installation</MudLink>.</li>
        <li>Scaffolded a project with <code>dotnet new shift</code> — <MudLink Href="/get-started/template-parameters">Template parameters</MudLink>.</li>
        <li>Have a SQL Server instance running locally. <b>LocalDB</b> (ships with Visual Studio / SQL Server Express LocalDB) is the easiest option for development.</li>
    </ul>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Step 1: Configure the connection string">
    <p>
        Open <code>YourApp.API/appsettings.Development.json</code>. The template ships
        with a connection string pointing at <code>localhost\sqlexpress</code> — that
        won't exist on most machines. Change both <code>SQLServer</code> and
        <code>LiveIdentitySQLServer</code> to point at whatever SQL Server you actually
        have running.
    </p>

    <p>For LocalDB, the connection string looks like this:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-json">"ConnectionStrings": {
  "SQLServer": "Server=(localdb)\\MSSQLLocalDB;Database=MyFirstShiftApp;Integrated Security=True;TrustServerCertificate=True;",
  "LiveIdentitySQLServer": "Server=(localdb)\\MSSQLLocalDB;Database=MyFirstShiftApp;Integrated Security=True;TrustServerCertificate=True;"
}</code></pre>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Note">
        Both connection strings can point at the same database for development. In
        production, <code>LiveIdentitySQLServer</code> typically points at a separate
        identity database — but you can ignore that distinction until you actually
        need it.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

