<DocSection Title="Step 4: Run the API">
    <p>
        Always run the <b>API</b> project — it hosts the Blazor WebAssembly bundle
        from <code>YourApp.Web</code> as well as the backing endpoints, so a single
        command brings up the whole app:
    </p>
    <DocSnippet Name="RunApi" Language="bash" />

    <p>On first run, the API does several things in order:</p>
    <ol>
        <li>Connects to the database you configured in Step 1.</li>
        <li>Verifies migrations are up to date.</li>
        <li>Runs the seed routine — creates a default country (<code>IQ</code>), region (<code>KRG</code>), company (<code>SFT</code>), and an initial admin user.</li>
        <li>Starts listening on the port from <code>launchSettings.json</code> (typically 5069 in development, varies per scaffold).</li>
    </ol>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Step 5: Open the app">
    <p>
        Look at the console output for a line like <code>Now listening on: http://localhost:5069</code> —
        that's the URL to open in your browser. The Blazor WebAssembly bundle loads from there.
    </p>

    <p>The default admin credentials seeded by the template are:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Username:</b> <code>SuperUser</code></li>
        <li><b>Password:</b> <code>OneTwo</code></li>
    </ul>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Warning">
        These credentials exist for first-run convenience and are <b>not safe</b> for
        any environment that anyone else can reach. Change the password immediately
        in non-trivial development setups, and never use these defaults in production.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Common errors on first run">
    <h3>Login failed for user, or Cannot open database</h3>
    <p>
        Your connection string in Step 1 is wrong, or the SQL instance isn't running.
        Double-check that the server name matches exactly what your SQL setup uses.
        For LocalDB, run <code>sqllocaldb info</code> in a terminal to confirm the
        instance name.
    </p>

    <h3>More than one DbContext was found</h3>
    <p>
        You forgot the <code>--context DB</code> flag in Step 2 or Step 3. The EF
        tools can't guess which context you mean when there are multiple registered.
    </p>

    <h3>Invalid object name 'ShiftIdentity.Countries'</h3>
    <p>
        You skipped Step 2 (creating the initial migration). The schema is empty so
        the seed code can't find the identity tables it expects. Run
        <code>dotnet ef migrations add InitialCreate --context DB ...</code> and try again.
    </p>

    <h3>Token public key cannot be null</h3>
    <p>
        The API was started without the <code>Development</code> environment, so
        <code>appsettings.Development.json</code> never loaded. Make sure
        <code>ASPNETCORE_ENVIRONMENT=Development</code> is set, or run via Visual
        Studio / <code>dotnet run</code> from the project directory (both load the
        Development profile by default).
    </p>
</DocSection>

